American-style pie is a remarkably versatile dessert. These broadly fall into three categories: custard pies, like pumpkin and applesauce, meringue pies like lemon meringue and banana cream, and stewed fruit pies like blueberry and apple.

Custard pies are the most versatile in terms of flavor and simple to prepare. Although pumpkin pie is not typically thought of as a custard, it is easier to think of it as eggs set with milk, which happen to have some puree which loosens the texture slightly. The puree can be flavored as desired (as long as the texture is not too loose), and need not be sweet (although typically it is). Minor variations in recipes come from adjusting the puree to achieve the necessary consistency to set.

Stewed fruit pies are also simple. Most fruits release water as they cook, like blueberries and apples. If they are stewed beforehand with sugar, the juice from the fruits will form a thick syrup with the flavor of the fruit, which can act as pie filling.

Meringue pies are the most simple conceptually, and are simply another type of pie with a meringue baked on top.

= Custard Pie Recipe
== Ingredients
- 9 inch piecrust
- 3 eggs
- $1/2$ cup milk
- 2 cups puree
- salt

== Directions
- Mix in eggs and milk with puree
- Pour into pie crust
- Bake at $350^circle F$ for 45$+epsilon$ minutes.

